Terraform Concepts Demonstrated
Concept	Where Used	Purpose
terraform block	Provider definition	Specifies required provider and version
Provider	provider "aws"	Connects Terraform to AWS
Variables	aws_region, vpc_cidr, web_subnet, private_subnet	Makes the configuration reusable
Locals	project_tags, ports	Stores reusable values within the module
Resources	VPC, Subnets, IGW, Route Table, EC2, Security Group	Creates AWS infrastructure
Data Source	data "aws_ami"	Reads the latest Ubuntu AMI without creating it
for_each	Subnets, Route Associations, EC2 Instances	Creates multiple resources from a map
Dynamic Blocks	Security Group ingress and egress	Generates repeated nested blocks programmatically
Functions	merge(), file()	Combines maps and reads local files
Outputs	VPC ID, Subnet IDs, Public IPs	Displays useful values after terraform apply
Suggested Improvements

A few changes would make this configuration more production-ready:

Set map_public_ip_on_launch = false for the private subnets.
Remove the for_each loop from the egress block and use a single "allow all" rule, since the loop creates identical rules.
Uncomment and configure the NAT Gateway, Elastic IP, and private route table so private subnets have outbound internet access.
Use variables for values such as instance_type and key_name to support multiple environments.
Add an output for the private subnet IDs if you'll use them in later modules.
Consider splitting the configuration into separate files (provider.tf, variables.tf, network.tf, security.tf, compute.tf, outputs.tf) or reusable modules as the project grows.

This configuration is an excellent hands-on example because it combines networking, security, compute, loops, dynamic blocks, data sources, and outputs into a single deployable Terraform project.
